Rating: 4
This was an absolutely delicious recipe, more so because this was my first time cooking with quinoa. Very simple, very filling and worked wonderfully with the grilled tuna steaks we made that night. My only caution would be after you have drained the grain and have it in the "sieve" to steam, be careful what you use for your sieve. Unthinkingly, I used a fine mesh, hand held strainer which fit nicely in my pot. Covered it with towel and lid as directed. Went to remove from heat after the 10 minutes were up and... whoops. The plastic handle had softened and folded and dropped the grain back into the simmering water. Live and learn!

Rating: 4
Great recipe! Good way to get the family to eat quinoa, which they usually don't like. I used olive oil instead of butter, which I usually do anyway. As far as the pros and cons of straining and resteaming, I thought it made a HUGE difference, much fluffier, nothing stuck together. I used a fine "screen" strainer which should hold the grains in, but I added cheesecloth anyway which I think added to the great texture. Love this! Made with the pork chops, which, BTW uses the same marinade I've been using for years. I put cilantro in almost everything! It's the same vinagrette I use as a standard salad dressing at home.

Rating: 4
The process of boiling and then steaming the quinoa was a bit of a pain (I had to line my strainer with cheesecloth to prevent the grains from falling through the holes), but it resulted in a fluffier, nuttier end product, which I appreciated. The recipe is seriously delicious, and I am eager to try it out with other grains (farro, barley, brown rice) and cous cous in the future.

